# Java Code Quality — Kafka Tool

## Style and conventions

- Match existing code: tabs for indentation in this project, `var` where type is obvious.
- Keep classes focused; prefer extending existing abstractions (`AbstractKafkaToolStage`, `KafkaAgnosticConsumer`, `ScreenBuilder`) over new parallel patterns.
- Use SLF4J for logging (`LoggerFactory.getLogger`); no `System.out.println` in production code.
- Mutable state belongs in services or JavaFX nodes; immutable data carriers belong in `inspect/` and `viewmodels/`.

### Imports

- Always import types; use the simple class name in code.
- Fully qualified names are allowed **only** when two types share the same simple name (name collision).
- Generated code (e.g. Protobuf) is exempt.

```java
// ❌ BAD
var topics = java.util.List.of("orders");

// ✅ GOOD
import java.util.List;
var topics = List.of("orders");

// ✅ OK — name collision
import java.util.Date;
var created = new java.sql.Date(System.currentTimeMillis());
```

### Static imports

- Static-import constants and static methods whose names read clearly at the call site.
- Skip static import when the method name is ambiguous without its owning class (e.g. multiple `of`/`get` imports in one file).

```java
// ❌ BAD
Platform.runLater(() -> table.getItems().add(row));

// ✅ GOOD
import static javafx.application.Platform.runLater;
runLater(() -> table.getItems().add(row));

// ✅ GOOD — meaningful assertion names
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertTrue;
assertTrue(result.valid());
```

### Records

- Prefer `record` for immutable data carriers (DTOs, results, config snapshots) over classes with getters only.
- Use a class when you need mutable state, inheritance, or non-trivial lifecycle behaviour.

```java
// ✅ GOOD
public record ConnectionResult(boolean success, String message, BrokerStatus status) {}
```

### Tell, Don't Ask

- Objects should **do** work; callers should not pull state out only to branch elsewhere.
- Put validation, transitions, and domain decisions on the type that owns the data (`inspect/`, `settings/`, `consumers/`).
- Controllers orchestrate UI flow; they should not re-implement domain rules via getter chains.

```java
// ❌ BAD — ask, then act outside
if (!broker.isValid()) {
    showErrors(broker.validationErrors());
    return;
}
connect(broker);

// ✅ GOOD — tell the object to act
broker.validate()
    .ifValid(() -> connect(broker))
    .ifInvalid(this::showErrors);
```

### String formatting

- Avoid string concatenation with `+` for dynamic messages; use a format template and `.formatted(...)`.
- For SLF4J logging, use parameterized messages (`log.info("Topic {} failed", topic)`) — not concatenation or `.formatted()`.

```java
// ❌ BAD
var message = "Label: " + label;
throw new IllegalStateException("Failed on topic " + topic + ": " + cause.getMessage());

// ✅ GOOD
var message = "Label: %s".formatted(label);
throw new IllegalStateException("Failed on topic %s: %s".formatted(topic, cause.getMessage()));

// ✅ GOOD — logging
log.warn("Failed on topic {}", topic, cause);
```


```java
// ❌ BAD — Kafka client in UI stage
var consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);

// ✅ GOOD — delegate to consumers/ or inspect/
KafkaAgnosticConsumer.json().start(broker, topic, callback);
adminService.listTopics(topics -> Platform.runLater(() -> listView.getItems().setAll(topics)));
```

- `inspect/` and `consumers/` must not import `javafx.*`.
- UI code must not construct `AdminClient` or `KafkaConsumer` directly.
- Settings changes go through `Settings.update*` methods only.

## JavaFX thread safety

```java
// ❌ BAD — UI update from executor/Kafka thread
messageTable.getItems().add(message);

// ✅ GOOD
Platform.runLater(() -> messageTable.getItems().add(message));
```

## Error handling

- Catch specific exceptions; log with context (topic name, broker, operation).
- Wrap irrecoverable consumer errors in `AgnosticConsumerException`.
- Do not swallow exceptions silently; at minimum log at ERROR level.
- Surface user-visible failures with JavaFX `Alert`, not stack traces in UI.

## Kafka API usage

- Use Kafka 4.x APIs: `DescribeTopicsResult.allTopicNames()`, not removed `all()`.
- Keep Confluent serializer config (`SCHEMA_REGISTRY_URL_CONFIG`) wired from `KafkaBroker`.
- Blocking poll loops belong on a dedicated executor, never the FX thread.

## Tests

- Follow `.cursor/rules/tdd-gherkin.mdc`: every feature ships with a Gherkin-style scenario using `Feature.feature(...).scenario(...).start()` in try-with-resources.
- Add unit tests for new logic in `settings/`, `consumers/`, `inspect/`, `controls/helpers/`.
- Use JUnit 5; one `@Test` method = one Scenario.
- Tests must not depend on a running Kafka broker unless tagged `@Tag("integration")`.
- Clean up `~/.kafka-tool/` in settings tests (see `SettingsTest`).

## Dependencies

- Bump library versions in `pom.xml` `<properties>` only; keep `kafka.version` and `confluent.version` compatible.
- Do not add dependencies without a clear use in the layer that needs them.

## Before finishing

- Run `mvn verify` and fix compilation/test failures.
- Avoid deprecated APIs; resolve compiler `-Xlint:deprecation` warnings when touching affected code.
